The following are some important things to know about current treatments for Ebola:

* There is currently no specific FDA approved treatment for Ebola. However, several investigational drugs and therapies have been used in previous outbreaks. These include ZMapp (an antibody cocktail), Remdesivir (antiviral drug) and Convalescent Plasma Therapy (CPT) which involves giving blood from recovered patients to infected individuals. It’s important to note that these options remain experimental and their safety and efficacy have yet to be fully established through randomized controlled trials.

* Clinical management remains an essential part of treating Ebola. This includes providing fluids and electrolytes, oxygen supplementation, blood transfusions and other general supportive care measures to help manage symptoms like fever, vomiting, diarrhea and dehydration. In severe cases, this can also involve dialysis for kidney failure or mechanical ventilation for respiratory distress.

* Vaccines have played a key role in controlling recent outbreaks. The two most widely used vaccines are RV521 (BioNTech/Moderna) and Ad5GHZ4 (Janssen Pharmaceutical). Both were developed using emergency procedures during the DRC outbreak and have shown high levels of effectiveness. They work by stimulating the body’s immune system against the virus and provide long term protection. Other potential vaccine candidates are also being studied but have yet to undergo large scale clinical trials.
